The front panel of the card features a variety of outputs, such as DisplayPort 1.4a and HDMI 2.1. For cooling, Gigabyte implemented the WINDFORCE 3X cooling system. The three fans feature alternate spinning to reduce turbulence and increase airflow pressure. The 3D Active Fan provides semi-passive cooling, and the fans will remain off when the GPU is processing a low load or low-power game. review_1: EDIT: ITS CHIP IS A PROTOTYPE/BETA VERSION! Using CPUID's hardware monitor, the gpu's information was named 'TRIAL', indicating them as prototypes or beta version. This explains why i'm getting lower core clocks than expected. It is a stripped down 5700xt, comparable to the rx 5600xt/rx 5700according to 3DMark banchmarks. GPU-Z reports its core clock to be the supposed values of a 5700xt but MSI afterburner and AMD's Adrenaline Software report it to have a core clock of 1390MHz and I was only able to boost it at exactly 1431MHz. Memory clock was okay and was running at it's supposed speed (1780MHz). Power consumption can only be boosted to 20% in afterburner. Any values other than these, it only goes back to the original values. It seems like the manufacturer locked any overclocking capabilities of this card. This might be to compensate the substandard cooling system installed in it. The model I got seems to have (painted?) aluminium heatpipes unlike the 'seemingly' copper ones displayed in the pictures. I also noticed some crooked heatsinks. But overall, by the looks of it, its a well refurbished gpu; no marks of it being used (dust, scratches etc)
